### The `never` Exhaustiveness Check — Precise Pattern

Both switch statements use the same idiom:

```typescript
default: {
  const _: never = action;
  throw new Error(`Unhandled deploy action kind: ${JSON.stringify(_)}`);
}
```

The assignment `const _: never = action` is the TypeScript compile-time enforcement: if a new `kind` is added to the `DeployAction` union without a corresponding `case`, TypeScript will flag this line with a type error (`Type 'NewKindAction' is not assignable to type 'never'`), forcing the implementer to handle the new kind before the code compiles. The `throw` after it is the runtime safety net for any JavaScript-only callers that bypass type checking.

